Think carefully about the theoretical limits of what file-level static analysis can and cannot determine about code quality, and design a principled classification of which quality analyses require interprocedural or cross-file analysis to be meaningful versus those that are genuinely self-contained within a single file.

Start by defining the analysis scope hierarchy: intra-function (only the AST of a single function), intra-file (all functions and classes in one file plus import declarations), inter-file single package (all files in one directory or module), project-wide (all files plus dependency information), and runtime (dynamic analysis). For each of the following quality dimensions, reason through which scope is the minimum required for a reliable (low false positive) result and what degrades if you use a narrower scope. Cover: cyclomatic and cognitive complexity (trivially intra-function), code duplication (inter-file), coupling metrics like CBO (project-wide or inter-file at minimum), SOLID principle violations (different principles require different scopes — analyze each separately), thread safety and race conditions (typically requires interprocedural dataflow), technical debt estimation (requires cross-file context for design debt but not code debt), type coverage (intra-file for annotation presence, but type correctness requires project-wide), and resource cleanup correctness (requires interprocedural analysis to trace resource lifetimes). Then reason about the engineering trade-off: a tool that stays strictly within file-level analysis is fast, scalable, and parallelizable, while project-wide analysis is slower but catches more real issues. What is the right default for a CI-integrated tool that must complete in under two minutes for a 100,000 line codebase? Propose a concrete two-tier architecture where fast file-level checks run on every commit and slower project-wide checks run on a schedule.
